oles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH004947%2F1"><gtr:id>D3DFBCA7-20A3-4697-929D-3F03C5DBDD10</gtr:id><gtr:title>Whose Heritage? Local and International Perspectives on Djenn&amp;eacute;, a World Heritage Site in Mali</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H004947/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Charlotte Joy's research is an investigation of the politics of World Heritage in Djenne,&amp;nbsp; a mud-brick town in Mali. Djenne was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1988 due to its exceptional architecture and archaeological sites. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Using a broad ethnographic approach to the investigation of cultural heritage issues in Djenne,&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;this research illuminates the limits of applying a static&amp;nbsp;approach to the conservation of cultural heritage in a context of extreme poverty, and instead suggests that a more fluid approach, such as that undertaken by UNESCO in relation to intangible heritage, may be of benefit. This ongoing research includes the study of the new European Union funded museum in Djenne, the impact of the Aga Khan Trust for Culture projects on the town and ongoing tensions between the local population and the heritage elite.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Charlotte Joy&amp;nbsp;is specialising in developing a comparative ethnographic approach to the study of cultural heritage politics and its relationship to development issues.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>75252</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E940972B-8C9B-49D0-94D3-A43666BFBE15</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cultural Landscape Heritage in Sub-Saharan Africa</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/bda2bb39b3cc8f0c58e49506d55db1ac"><gtr:id>bda2bb39b3cc8f0c58e49506d55db1ac</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Beardsley John</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780884024101</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>56de5e75d68374.10216611</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/H004947/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</